But his glory‚ his peculiar excellence, was his colouring3 there was a charin about it, a thing that could not be understood, but was felt. How transparent its depth,—-how fresh,-—how rich to gorgeousness,—how luminous‚ as from within !

His power over expression was inferior to his colouring. Not that he can be justly said to have failed in his exercise of this faculty 3 he rather did not attempt its highest range. His mind lin- gered delighted, at his eye, and if his mind did proceed inwards, it soon returned, and contented itself with that form of expression which, if we may so speak, lies in closest contact with material beauty. Therefore it is that he often brought out, with great felicity and force, some simple feeling, ' some fixed type of character common to a class, but did not care to ascend to the highest heaven of invention, or stir the depths of imagination and passion.
